OL,3,CIsolation heightens 'threat vigilance'
OL,4,Cin teenagers, study suggests
OL,6,FTeenagers who spend time cooped up in
OL,7,Ftheir bedrooms may be more prone to
OL,8,Ffeeling threatened, research suggests.
OL,10,FA new study found that people in their
OL,11,Flate teens experience an increased
OL,12,Fsensitivity to threats after just a
OL,13,Ffew hours left in a room on their own,
OL,14,Fand this effect endures even if they
OL,15,Fare interacting with others online.
OL,17,FThe findings might shed light on the
OL,18,Flink between loneliness and mental
OL,19,Fhealth conditions such as anxiety
OL,20,Fdisorders, which are on the rise in
OL,21,Fyoung people, experts suggest.
