OL,3,CIsolation heightens 'threat vigilance'
OL,4,Cin teenagers, study suggests
OL,6,FThey say their experiment ` which saw
OL,7,F40 young people aged 16-19 undergo
OL,8,Ftesting before and after several hours
OL,9,Falone ` both with and without their
OL,10,Fsmartphones, is the first to find an
OL,11,Fincreased threat response triggered by
OL,12,Fisolation in humans.
OL,14,FEmily Towner, study lead author from
OL,15,Fthe University of Cambridge's
OL,16,FDepartment of Psychology, said: "We
OL,17,Fdetected signs of heightened threat
OL,18,Fvigilance after a few hours of
OL,19,Fisolation, even when the adolescents
OL,20,Fhad been connected through smartphones
OL,21,Fand social media."
