OL,3,CIsolation heightens 'threat vigilance'
OL,4,Cin teenagers, study suggests
OL,6,FShe added: "This alertness to
OL,7,Fperceived threats might be the same
OL,8,Fmechanism that leads to the excessive
OL,9,Fworry and inability to feel safe which
OL,10,Fcharacterises anxiety.
OL,12,F"It makes evolutionary sense that
OL,13,Fbeing alone increases our vigilance to
OL,14,Fpotential threats.
OL,16,F"These threat response mechanisms
OL,17,Fundergo a lot of changes in
OL,18,Fadolescence, a stage of life marked by
OL,19,Fincreasing independence and social
OL,20,Fsensitivity.
