OL,3,CIsolation heightens 'threat vigilance'
OL,4,Cin teenagers, study suggests
OL,6,FOne of the tests was a Pavlovian
OL,7,Fthreat test, in which the teenagers
OL,8,Fwere shown a series of shapes on a
OL,9,Fscreen, one of which was paired with a
OL,10,Fharsh noise played through headphones,
OL,11,Fso the shape became associated with a
OL,12,Ffeeling of apprehension.
OL,14,FAccording to the findings, periods of
OL,15,Fisolation, including those in which
OL,16,Fthe teenagers could use their phones,
OL,17,Fled to an increased threat response `
OL,18,Fthe sensing of and reacting to
OL,19,Fpotential dangers.
